To terminate a C program, you can use the `return` statement at the end of the `main()` function. For example:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");
    return 0;  // This terminates the program
}
```

Alternatively, you can use `exit()` from the `stdlib.h` library to terminate the program immediately, regardless of where it is called:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");
    exit(0);  // This terminates the program immediately
}
```

Note: `return 0` indicates successful termination, while `return 1` or other non-zero values indicate an error. `exit()` can take any integer value and will terminate the program immediately.
